        <description> </description>
        <content:encoded>&lt;p&gt;In the Facebook group &lt;em&gt;Mathematical Mathematics Memes&lt;/em&gt;, someone &lt;a href=&#34;https://www.facebook.com/groups/1567682496877142/posts/2882359472076098&#34;&gt;posted&lt;/a&gt;:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Tell me your area of specialization by writing a poem containing what you studied.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In the past, I&amp;rsquo;ve tried and failed to come up with a succint summary of my thesis for &lt;a href=&#34;https://lolmythesis.com/&#34;&gt;lol my thesis&lt;/a&gt;. But my poem seemed to be popular:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Roses are red&lt;br /&gt;
Violets are blue&lt;br /&gt;
A random eigenfunction of the Laplacian on the flat torus of dimension $d$ with eigenvalue $\lambda$ asymptotically has an expected value of $O(\lambda^d)$ nodal domains as $\lambda$ tends to infinity with exponentially concentrated probability distribution&lt;br /&gt;
And so do you&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&#34;https://shorts.yonispants.com/images/content/fb-thesis-poem.png&#34; style=&#34;width: 50%;&#34; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Note - the poem is not mathematically accurate, but it is close enough for all practical purposes.&lt;/p&gt;
</content:encoded>
